On a Sabbath, Jesus was walking through the fields with his disciples. The disciples began to pluck the heads of wheat.
The Pharisees said to Jesus, "Look! It is not lawful to do this on the Sabbath. Why are your disciples doing it?"
Reply, "What did David do? He and his men were hungry. They needed food."
This was at a time when Abiathar was high priest. David went into the house of God and ate the hallowed bread, which it was lawful only for the priests to eat. And he gave some to his men also.
Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath."
Therefore the Son of Man is also Lord of the Sabbath.
Healing on Saturday
Again Jesus entered the synagogue, and a man was there with a withered hand.
Some Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They watched him closely. They wanted to see whether he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus said to the man with the weak and twisted hand, "Stand up in front of everyone."
Then Jesus asked them, "What does the law say about the Sabbath? Is it right to do good or to do evil? To save a life or to kill?" But no one answered.
Jesus looked around at them with anger. He was very distressed because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." So he stretched it out, and his hand was restored as good as new.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how they might destroy Him. The multitudes followed Jesus.
Jesus went with his disciples to the Sea of Galilee. Large crowds from Galilee followed him.
The people heard about all that Jesus was doing. Large crowds came to him from Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, and the region around Tyre and Sidon.
Because of the crowds, Jesus told his disciples to prepare a small boat for him. This would keep people from crowding him.
Jesus healed many people. That's why those who were sick pushed to touch him.
